---
import ChapterLayout from "../layouts/ChapterLayout.astro";
import BinderHoles from "../components/BinderHoles.astro";
import Backlink from "../components/Backlink.astro";
---

<ChapterLayout title="Case Studies" headVoice="publisher">
  <div data-voice="publisher">
    <BinderHoles />
    <Backlink />
    <p class="eyebrow"><span>(Worked Examples of Play)</span></p>
    <blockquote>
      <p>
        <span>The surest way to learn </span><a href="/table-of-contents"
          >Severed Story</a
        ><span>
          is to watch a workday unfold. What follows are a few worked examples —
          scenes narrated as they might happen at your table, with every Roll
          laid bare. Read them with
        </span><a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a><span>
          close at hand.</span>
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>Meet the Employee</span></h2>
    <p>
      <span>Across these examples we follow </span><strong
        ><span>Nina H.</span></strong
      ><span
        >, a refiner in Macrodata Refinement. Her HRPE assessed her as
      </span><strong><span>The Analyst (DR)</span></strong><span
        >. The parts of her LIEP that matter here:</span>
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>DREAD row:</span></strong><span>
            3 Temper Points, with
          </span><strong><span>WIT</span></strong><span>
            checked as a Core Competency, and 1 Kier Point.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>FROLIC row:</span></strong><span>
            2 Temper Points.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Stress:</span></strong><span>
            beginning the day at
          </span><strong><span>Satisfactory</span></strong><span>.</span>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>Example One — A Routine Request</span></h2>
    <p>
      <span
        >Nina&#x27;s Floor Manager asks her to fetch a file from a cabinet whose
        lock has jammed. The drawer is stubborn; the manager is watching.</span>
    </p>
    <p>
      <span>The GM decides the outcome is both </span><em
        ><span>uncertain</span></em
      ><span> (the lock is fighting her) and </span><em
        ><span>meaningful</span></em
      ><span> (her manager is judging her), so a </span><strong
        ><span>Roll</span></strong
      ><span>
        is called. The action — careful, quick problem-solving under a
        superior&#x27;s eye — is best embodied by
      </span><strong><span>WIT</span></strong><span
        >, whose parent Temper is
      </span><strong><span>DREAD</span></strong><span
        >. The GM sets the Task Severity at
      </span><strong><span>Demanding (15)</span></strong><span>.</span>
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u><span>Nina&#x27;s Roll</span></u></strong></p>
      <p>
        <strong><span>Principle:</span></strong><span>
          WIT (DREAD row) &nbsp;·&nbsp;
        </span><strong><span>Task Severity:</span></strong><span>
          Demanding (15)</span>
      </p>
      <p>
        <span>WIT is a </span><strong><span>Core Competency</span></strong><span
          >, so Nina rolls with
        </span><strong><span>Confidence</span></strong><span
          >. The action serves Lumon, so her
        </span><strong><span>Kier Point</span></strong><span>
          in the DREAD row applies.</span>
      </p>
      <p>
        <span>2d20 → </span><strong><span>9</span></strong><span>
          and
        </span><strong><span>16</span></strong><span> — take the 16.</span>
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong><span>16 + 3 Temper + 1 Kier = 20.</span></strong><span>
          20 ≥ 15 →
        </span><strong><span>Success.</span></strong>
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      <span
        >The lock yields with a satisfying clunk. Nina hands the file over; her
        manager offers a rare, warm nod. A small, wholesome moment — the kind a
        quiet quarter is built from.</span>
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>Example Two — A Bad Afternoon</span></h2>
    <p>
      <span
        >Hours later, the day has worn on Nina. A string of interruptions has
        pushed her stress up to
      </span><strong><span>Poor</span></strong><span
        >. When a rattled coworker snaps at her over a shared terminal, she
        tries to calm them down.</span>
    </p>
    <p>
      <span>The GM rules this a </span><strong><span>CHEER</span></strong><span>
        action (parent Temper
      </span><strong><span>FROLIC</span></strong><span
        >) — not one of Nina&#x27;s Core Competencies. And because she is at
      </span><strong><span>Poor</span></strong><span
        >, the GM exercises the option to impose
      </span><strong><span>Hesitance</span></strong><span>
        on the Roll. Task Severity:
      </span><strong><span>Demanding (15)</span></strong><span>.</span>
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u><span>Nina&#x27;s Roll</span></u></strong></p>
      <p>
        <strong><span>Principle:</span></strong><span>
          CHEER (FROLIC row) &nbsp;·&nbsp;
        </span><strong><span>Task Severity:</span></strong><span>
          Demanding (15) &nbsp;·&nbsp;
        </span><strong><span>Hesitance</span></strong>
      </p>
      <p>
        <span>2d20 → </span><strong><span>11</span></strong><span>
          and
        </span><strong><span>1</span></strong><span>
          — Hesitance takes the
        </span><strong><span>lower</span></strong><span>: the 1.</span>
      </p>
      <p>
        <span>A natural </span><strong><span>1</span></strong><span>
          is a
        </span><strong><span>Critical Failure</span></strong><span
          >, regardless of Modifiers.
        </span><strong><span>Nina&#x27;s stress rises by 1.</span></strong>
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      <span
        >Nina says exactly the wrong thing. The coworker recoils, wounded, and
        stalks off — and now there is bad blood between them. The GM rules this
        a
      </span><strong><span>Problem</span></strong><span
        >: Nina writes a &quot;P&quot; in her left-most stress box and notes the
        grudge under
      </span><strong><span>Stress Related Circumstances</span></strong><span
        >. Unlike ordinary stress, a Problem&#x27;s mark will not wipe clean
        with tomorrow&#x27;s descent — it must be
      </span><em><span>resolved through play</span></em><span> first.</span>
    </p>
    <p>
      <span
        >One natural 1 has turned a small slight into a thread the GM can pull
        for workdays to come. That is the engine of
      </span><a href="/table-of-contents">Severed Story</a><span>
        doing its work.</span>
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><em><strong><span>The Other Path.</span></strong></em></p>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >The handbook ends Nina&#x27;s scene the moment she serves Lumon.
              Of course it does. But look at what it skips past: the drawer is
              open, and a name she knows is staring up at her.</span
            ></em>
        </p>
        <p><em><span>She could take a page.</span></em></p>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >That is not the cabinet roll — that one is finished and won.
              Slipping a page up her sleeve under a manager&#x27;s eye is a
              separate act, and so it earns a separate, additional Roll: a new
              one, this time under
            </span></em
          ><em><strong><span>WILES</span></strong></em><em
            ><span>
              (the MALICE row), made in secret. No Core Competency to lean on
              this time, and no Kier Point to spend — because this act does not
              serve them. It serves
            </span></em
          ><em><u><span>her</span></u></em><em><span>. So it is her </span></em
          ><em><strong><span>Ricken Points</span></strong></em><em
            ><span>
              that carry the Roll, and a success <strong>may</strong> earn her a Ricken
              Point into that row, if the GM feels that this moment of defiance calls
              for it. Should she fail it, the manager catches the motion of her hand
              — and that is a Problem all her own.</span
            ></em>
        </p>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >One workday. One jammed drawer. But two separate Rolls living
              inside it — the one they asked her to make, and the one they would
              never know she made.</span
            ></em>
        </p>
        <p><em><strong><span>— C.C.</span></strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <hr />
    <p>
      <span>That is play in </span><a href="/table-of-contents"
        >Severed Story</a
      ><span>. The rest is the story you and your players tell with it.</span>
    </p>
    <p><span>Enjoy your time within these hallowed halls!</span></p>
  </div>
</ChapterLayout>
